      "content": "Imagine a two-dimensional plane where your coefficients are plotted. The L1 penalty creates a diamond-shaped constraint, with the axes being the lines where the coefficients are zero. When you minimize the cost function with this diamond constraint, the solution can lie on the axes, which are the points where the diamond intersects, thus hitting the axes and making some coefficients exactly zero. The L2 penalty, however, creates a circular constraint centered at the origin. This circle is always positive and never intersects the axes, so the solution will always lie within the circle, keeping the coefficients small but never exactly zero.",
